WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.780 --> 00:00:06.210
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress, in Washington D.C.

00:00:06.210 --> 00:00:07.910
&gt;&gt; Jessica Flynn: Kaitlyn
Greenidge's complex

00:00:07.910 --> 00:00:11.700
and gripping debut novel, "We
Love You, Charlie Freeman,"

00:00:11.700 --> 00:00:15.180
follows the story of an African
American family, the Freemans,

00:00:15.180 --> 00:00:18.690
as they uproot their lives and
move to a research facility

00:00:18.690 --> 00:00:21.900
in a largely white
part of the Berkshires.

00:00:21.900 --> 00:00:25.080
The Freemans are fluent in sign
language, and they've been hired

00:00:25.080 --> 00:00:28.830
to live with a chimpanzee named
Charlie to raise him as a member

00:00:28.830 --> 00:00:30.680
of their family and to
teach him sign language.

00:00:30.680 --> 00:00:37.380
As the family saga at the institute
unfolds, so does the 1929 story

00:00:37.380 --> 00:00:40.410
of a schoolteacher whose
encounters with a white doctor

00:00:40.410 --> 00:00:44.160
from the institute, painfully
illuminate both the past

00:00:44.160 --> 00:00:46.560
and the present.

00:00:46.560 --> 00:00:50.740 position:56%
Released earlier this year to much
acclaim, Publishers Weekly described

00:00:50.740 --> 00:00:55.420
"We Love You, Charlie Freeman," as
ambitious and deftly constructed,

00:00:55.420 --> 00:00:59.850
encompassing weighty issues such
as race, language, sexuality,

00:00:59.850 --> 00:01:02.840
and the intersections
of religion and science,

00:01:02.840 --> 00:01:06.230
and calling it a sobering look at
how we communicate with one another

00:01:06.230 --> 00:01:10.560
and what inevitably gets
lost in translation.

00:01:10.560 --> 00:01:12.060
Greenidge was born in Boston,

00:01:12.060 --> 00:01:15.350
and received her MFA
from Hunter College.

00:01:15.350 --> 00:01:17.670
She's started writing the
novel during her first semester

00:01:17.670 --> 00:01:20.470
of graduate school, during
which time she also worked

00:01:20.470 --> 00:01:24.410
as a historical researcher
at a Black history museum.

00:01:24.410 --> 00:01:28.940
Her writing has appeared in The
Believer, American Short Fiction,

00:01:28.940 --> 00:01:32.650
The Feminist Wire, Afro-Pot
Magazine, The New York Times,

00:01:32.650 --> 00:01:34.650
and many other publications.

00:01:34.650 --> 00:01:36.000
And she has received fellowships

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:39.320
from the Lower Manhattan Community
Council's Workspace Program,

00:01:39.320 --> 00:01:41.820
and the Bread Loaf
Writers Conference.

00:01:41.820 --> 00:01:46.150
She is also a recent recipient
of a literature fellowship

00:01:46.150 --> 00:01:48.170
from the National Endowment
for the Arts.

00:01:48.170 --> 00:01:51.000
This is a highly competitive
fellowship based solely

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:56.180 position:56%
on artistic excellence and selected
through an anonymous review process.

00:01:56.180 --> 00:01:58.250
If you're interested in learning
more about these fellowships,

00:01:58.250 --> 00:02:00.590
you can stop by our
table over there.

00:02:00.590 --> 00:02:03.510
Please join me in welcoming
Kaitlyn Greenidge.

00:02:03.510 --> 00:02:12.720
[ Applause ]

00:02:12.720 --> 00:02:15.520
&gt;&gt; Kaitlyn Greenidge: Hi,
so I'm Kaitlyn Greenidge.

00:02:15.520 --> 00:02:18.260
Thank you so much for coming today.

00:02:18.260 --> 00:02:21.980 position:56%
So I thought that I would first talk
a little bit about how the book came

00:02:21.980 --> 00:02:24.930
to be, because that's usually
people's first question

00:02:24.930 --> 00:02:26.580
when I tell them what
this book is about.

00:02:26.580 --> 00:02:29.600
So I thought I'd talk a little bit
about that, and then I might read

00:02:29.600 --> 00:02:33.990
from the first opening pages for
a little bit, and then open it

00:02:33.990 --> 00:02:35.460
up to questions from you guys.

00:02:35.460 --> 00:02:39.690 position:56%
And we can kind of have a, hopefully
a group conversation in the room.

00:02:39.690 --> 00:02:45.010
So, "We Love You, Charlie Freeman,"
as was very beautifully introduced,

00:02:45.010 --> 00:02:49.000
is about a Black family from
Boston that moves to a nearly,

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:52.950
all white town in the
Berkshires in the early 1990s.

00:02:52.950 --> 00:02:55.550
And they moved there to
take part in an experiment

00:02:55.550 --> 00:02:58.100
where they're teaching sign
language to a chimpanzee.

00:02:58.100 --> 00:03:03.030
So, that idea came
to me kind of as a

00:03:03.030 --> 00:03:05.430
like thunderbolt or
a lightning bolt.

00:03:05.430 --> 00:03:09.360 position:56%
I was at a bar in Brooklyn that used

00:03:09.360 --> 00:03:14.330
to have a lecture series
called "Adult Education."

00:03:14.330 --> 00:03:17.130
And they would do like quirky
lecture subjects every Saturday.

00:03:17.130 --> 00:03:19.650
And you would go and you would have
a drink and listen to these kind

00:03:19.650 --> 00:03:23.540
of strange, interesting pieces
about history and the past.

00:03:23.540 --> 00:03:26.190
And one time I went and then theme

00:03:26.190 --> 00:03:29.540
for the night was "Animals
and Deviance."

00:03:29.540 --> 00:03:34.990
And a woman gave a lecture about
this family named the Kelloggs.

00:03:34.990 --> 00:03:39.060
Was a married pair of
anthropologists in the 1920s,

00:03:39.060 --> 00:03:40.570 position:56%
and they decided to do an experiment

00:03:40.570 --> 00:03:44.040
where they raised their
son alongside a chimpanzee.

00:03:44.040 --> 00:03:46.140
They wrote a book about it called,
"The Ape and the Child," that came

00:03:46.140 --> 00:03:49.420
out towards the tail
end of the 1920s.

00:03:49.420 --> 00:03:51.100
And you can still find this book.

00:03:51.100 --> 00:03:54.590 position:56%
I actually, as soon as I heard about
this, I went to Amazon and I tried

00:03:54.590 --> 00:03:56.850
to find it and I got a copy of it.

00:03:56.850 --> 00:03:58.150
The reason why you
can still find it is

00:03:58.150 --> 00:04:00.320
because their studies
was really kind

00:04:00.320 --> 00:04:01.950
of like universally
panned by everybody.

00:04:01.950 --> 00:04:03.600
Everybody was kind of like,
"That is a crazy idea.

00:04:03.600 --> 00:04:05.540
Why would you ever do
that to your child?"

00:04:05.540 --> 00:04:06.840
kind of thing.

00:04:06.840 --> 00:04:08.410
And if you look through
the book, it's fascinating.

00:04:08.410 --> 00:04:13.530
They literally took their toddler
and then this young chimpanzee

00:04:13.530 --> 00:04:15.850
and put them side by side
and took photographs of them.

00:04:15.850 --> 00:04:20.870
And they do things like they shoot
off a revolver behind their heads

00:04:20.870 --> 00:04:23.600
and see who reacted fastest, the
first, and take a photograph of it.

00:04:23.600 --> 00:04:28.200
It just, all these really
interesting and wonderful images

00:04:28.200 --> 00:04:31.600
and really frightening
images are within this book.

00:04:31.600 --> 00:04:36.080
And so, when the Kelloggs
published the book in the 1920s,

00:04:36.080 --> 00:04:39.080
most of the anthropology
community was horrified,

00:04:39.080 --> 00:04:40.380
and so they quickly kind

00:04:40.380 --> 00:04:44.110
of distanced themselves
from this subject.

00:04:44.110 --> 00:04:46.400
And they gave the chimpanzee
actually back

00:04:46.400 --> 00:04:49.500
to the research facility
where they got her from.

00:04:49.500 --> 00:04:52.320
And then their son, when he
grew up many years later,

00:04:52.320 --> 00:04:53.620
he actually committed suicide.

00:04:53.620 --> 00:04:56.360
That was kind of like the
very sad coda to the story.

00:04:56.360 --> 00:05:00.090
So, I'm sitting in the audience and
I'm about to go into grad school

00:05:00.090 --> 00:05:02.520
for creative writing,
and I'm thinking, "Wow,

00:05:02.520 --> 00:05:04.430
that's a really fascinating story.

00:05:04.430 --> 00:05:07.790
That could probably be a really
great short story, and let me try

00:05:07.790 --> 00:05:10.980
and make this into what
it could possibly be."

00:05:10.980 --> 00:05:15.540
And at the same time, when
I was thinking about that,

00:05:15.540 --> 00:05:18.270
about that story and kind of all
that stuff was just kind of going

00:05:18.270 --> 00:05:20.710
through my brain, as was
said in the introduction,

00:05:20.710 --> 00:05:25.190
I was working as a researcher for
a Black history museum in Brooklyn,

00:05:25.190 --> 00:05:26.690
called the Weeksville
Heritage Center.

00:05:26.690 --> 00:05:28.740
If you've never been, you
should definitely check it out.

00:05:28.740 --> 00:05:30.040
It's in Crown Heights, Brooklyn.

00:05:30.040 --> 00:05:32.410
It's been around since 1968.

00:05:32.410 --> 00:05:33.970
Really fascinating museum.

00:05:33.970 --> 00:05:35.340
Wonderful resource.

00:05:35.340 --> 00:05:40.300
It's dedicated to the history of
the first free Black community

00:05:40.300 --> 00:05:44.070
in Brooklyn that was
founded in 1827.

00:05:44.070 --> 00:05:46.280
And it's been a continual
Black neighborhood

00:05:46.280 --> 00:05:49.590
in that area too, till today.

00:05:49.590 --> 00:05:51.910
So anyways, I was working
as a researcher there,

00:05:51.910 --> 00:05:56.390
and I had been working probably at
that point for the past ten years

00:05:56.390 --> 00:05:59.170
as a researcher, or some sort
of historical interpreter,

00:05:59.170 --> 00:06:02.780
for Black history sites either
in New York City or in Boston.

00:06:02.780 --> 00:06:06.550
And while I was doing that
work, a lot of the time,

00:06:06.550 --> 00:06:09.960
of what I was doing, was
kind of talking directly

00:06:09.960 --> 00:06:12.490
to people about Black history.

00:06:12.490 --> 00:06:17.820 position:56%
And for a little while, when I was
in Boston, I worked as a park ranger

00:06:17.820 --> 00:06:20.620
for the Black Heritage Trail,
which meant that I was kind

00:06:20.620 --> 00:06:21.920
of dressed like Smoky the Bear.

00:06:21.920 --> 00:06:27.200
Like I had a park ranger
uniform on, the park ranger hat,

00:06:27.200 --> 00:06:32.360
and I would stand in front of
the memorial to the 54th regiment

00:06:32.360 --> 00:06:34.370
which was the first
all-Black regiment to fight

00:06:34.370 --> 00:06:35.910
for the United States army.

00:06:35.910 --> 00:06:37.210
They made the movie
Glory about them.

00:06:37.210 --> 00:06:39.410
So I'd stand in front of this
memorial which is directly

00:06:39.410 --> 00:06:43.150
across the street from the Boston
State House, for four to five hours

00:06:43.150 --> 00:06:45.390
at a time, in the summertime,

00:06:45.390 --> 00:06:48.500
talking to tourists just
walking by, about Black history.

00:06:48.500 --> 00:06:52.930
And as you can imagine, those
conversations ranged and varied

00:06:52.930 --> 00:06:56.450
and were really interesting and
sometimes really hard to have.

00:06:56.450 --> 00:07:01.530 position:56%
So you would have people -- our tour
started where the Freedom Trail,

00:07:01.530 --> 00:07:04.460
which covers Boston's
Revolutionary War history ended.

00:07:04.460 --> 00:07:07.270 position:56%
So a lot of times, you'd have people
saying, "Where's the Freedom Trail?"

00:07:07.270 --> 00:07:09.480
And you would say, "It's
not the Freedom Trail.

00:07:09.480 --> 00:07:10.780
It's the Black History Trail.

00:07:10.780 --> 00:07:12.080
You want to come on it?"

00:07:12.080 --> 00:07:13.380
And then people would
kind of run away.

00:07:13.380 --> 00:07:15.430
Or you would say like,
"Are you interested

00:07:15.430 --> 00:07:16.730
in kind of talking about this?"

00:07:16.730 --> 00:07:18.910
And people would want to argue
with you about the causes

00:07:18.910 --> 00:07:21.950
of the Civil War or they'd want to
talk about the merits of slavery

00:07:21.950 --> 00:07:23.890
or who started slavery first.

00:07:23.890 --> 00:07:27.880
A lot of times, people wanted
to talk about really just --

00:07:27.880 --> 00:07:30.180
really only certain
moments of Black history.

00:07:30.180 --> 00:07:34.000
So, that particular site
that I worked at was talking

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:38.720 position:56%
about Boston's Black
Abolitionists Movement which started

00:07:38.720 --> 00:07:42.220
like basically at the same
time as the Revolutionary War.

00:07:42.220 --> 00:07:45.160
But people would really only kind
of want to talk about this --

00:07:45.160 --> 00:07:48.630
the Civil War for like these
four years of Black history.

00:07:48.630 --> 00:07:50.870
If they didn't want to talk about
that then they wanted to talk

00:07:50.870 --> 00:07:52.170
about the Civil Rights Movement.

00:07:52.170 --> 00:07:57.680
So another kind of very brief
moment in Black history.

00:07:57.680 --> 00:08:00.510
And you would -- I would say
to people like, "Oh this is --

00:08:00.510 --> 00:08:01.970
but this other thing happened

00:08:01.970 --> 00:08:04.050
and this person did
this really heroic act

00:08:04.050 --> 00:08:05.950
and this really interesting
thing happened," or whatever.

00:08:05.950 --> 00:08:07.870
And people would say, "Yes,
but let's get back to slavery.

00:08:07.870 --> 00:08:09.900
Can you tell us again
about slavery?"

00:08:09.900 --> 00:08:13.960
So, as I was in there and I'm kind
of standing there and if you work

00:08:13.960 --> 00:08:17.240
with Black history, these are
kind of arguments that we kind

00:08:17.240 --> 00:08:19.160
of always kind of come up
again, again and again,

00:08:19.160 --> 00:08:20.720
when we talk about Black history.

00:08:20.720 --> 00:08:24.120
It feels actually really fortuitous
that I'm here the same weekend

00:08:24.120 --> 00:08:26.330
that the museum --
the National Museum

00:08:26.330 --> 00:08:29.060
for African American History is
opening, which is so exciting

00:08:29.060 --> 00:08:35.400 position:56%
because all of a sudden, all of this
wonderful information is available

00:08:35.400 --> 00:08:37.510
to us on a much bigger stage

00:08:37.510 --> 00:08:41.240
and in a completely different
way than it has been before.

00:08:41.240 --> 00:08:44.280
So it feels, for me, I mean I
think everybody's really excited

00:08:44.280 --> 00:08:46.090
about that museum opening,
but for me,

00:08:46.090 --> 00:08:49.750
it just feels like it's a turning
point I think in how we're going

00:08:49.750 --> 00:08:54.110
to be able to process and think
about those things going forward.

00:08:54.110 --> 00:09:01.430 position:56%
So all of those things were circling
around my mind and I go and I sit

00:09:01.430 --> 00:09:04.540
down and I try and figure out
what are all those things mean

00:09:04.540 --> 00:09:06.890
and what do I actually want
to say about all those things?

00:09:06.890 --> 00:09:08.510
And what are the conversations
that I wish

00:09:08.510 --> 00:09:10.990
that we could have
about all those things?

00:09:10.990 --> 00:09:12.470
And what are the conversations
that I wish

00:09:12.470 --> 00:09:13.950
that we could have
about all those things?

00:09:13.950 --> 00:09:16.610
And what are the questions
that I wish that we could ask

00:09:16.610 --> 00:09:18.680
about all those things that
sometimes we either avoid asking

00:09:18.680 --> 00:09:20.730
or we don't feel like
asking of ourselves?

00:09:20.730 --> 00:09:22.940
And so that's kind of the
impetuous of the book,

00:09:22.940 --> 00:09:24.770
where the book came from.

00:09:24.770 --> 00:09:26.630
I really wanted to write and talk

00:09:26.630 --> 00:09:29.750
about a Black experience
in the northeast.

00:09:29.750 --> 00:09:32.910
So the book takes place
in Boston and in the --

00:09:32.910 --> 00:09:35.570
in western Massachusetts
in the Berkshires region.

00:09:35.570 --> 00:09:38.190
A lot of times, when people
talk about Black history

00:09:38.190 --> 00:09:40.680
and Black identity, it's
really centered in the south,

00:09:40.680 --> 00:09:44.480
and we know a little bit more
about southern Black experiences,

00:09:44.480 --> 00:09:47.500
but of course, Black
identity isn't a monolith.

00:09:47.500 --> 00:09:51.110
Black American identity
differs from region to region.

00:09:51.110 --> 00:09:53.390
There's rich history
in all of the regions.

00:09:53.390 --> 00:09:55.590
And so I got really interested
about that and especially

00:09:55.590 --> 00:10:02.660
when I was doing more research and
I came across these photo studies

00:10:02.660 --> 00:10:08.680
of -- well, photographs first that
I saw of integrated classrooms

00:10:08.680 --> 00:10:10.080
in the Berkshires in the 1890s.

00:10:10.080 --> 00:10:15.520
And Du Bois who of course
was a famous Black scholar,

00:10:15.520 --> 00:10:17.950
he actually grew up in Western
Massachusetts in the Berkshires

00:10:17.950 --> 00:10:19.550
and I thought, "Wow,
that's really fascinating.

00:10:19.550 --> 00:10:23.370
That has to somehow address that
or talk about that in the book.

00:10:23.370 --> 00:10:27.070
And then also finding out that
Du Bois himself did these really

00:10:27.070 --> 00:10:30.150
interesting photographic studies

00:10:30.150 --> 00:10:32.500
of Black people throughout
the United States,

00:10:32.500 --> 00:10:34.710
in the 1890s and early 1900s.

00:10:34.710 --> 00:10:37.400
And he made a big album
of them and presented it

00:10:37.400 --> 00:10:40.050
at the Paris Exhibition
in the 1900s.

00:10:40.050 --> 00:10:43.560
So it feels like there's all these
kind of themes and things that come

00:10:43.560 --> 00:10:47.000
up again and again, kind of
undercurrents, in history,

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:50.810
that I kept getting more and
more interested of talking about

00:10:50.810 --> 00:10:53.430
and thinking about and trying
to work into a narrative.

00:10:53.430 --> 00:10:58.780
If you can't tell by now, my
training is to be a researcher.

00:10:58.780 --> 00:11:01.290
I'm not really a natural
storyteller.

00:11:01.290 --> 00:11:06.940
I love finding interesting and
wonderful facts that are hidden

00:11:06.940 --> 00:11:10.630
in archives and other places,
and bringing them up and trying

00:11:10.630 --> 00:11:12.810
to get people to talk about them.

00:11:12.810 --> 00:11:16.290
So, getting all of those
interesting bits of information

00:11:16.290 --> 00:11:19.160
into an actual narrative,
was really difficult

00:11:19.160 --> 00:11:20.460
and took a really long time.

00:11:20.460 --> 00:11:23.490 position:56%
So I started this book in fall 2008,

00:11:23.490 --> 00:11:25.910
and it was published
in March of this year.

00:11:25.910 --> 00:11:27.860
So it took a really long
time to figure out how

00:11:27.860 --> 00:11:31.920
to dramatize those things and
make them into a book that --

00:11:31.920 --> 00:11:34.300
in a story that feels natural

00:11:34.300 --> 00:11:36.430
and that you will kind
of want to follow along.

00:11:36.430 --> 00:11:39.150
And I think like probably everybody
who's at this book festival,

00:11:39.150 --> 00:11:43.310 position:56%
I love novels and I love books, but
for a long time of those eight years

00:11:43.310 --> 00:11:46.720
and before that as well, it felt
like a huge kind of leap to be able

00:11:46.720 --> 00:11:49.630
to get to the point of putting
all those things that I love

00:11:49.630 --> 00:11:53.290
and that I'm interested in, into
an actual novel that's going

00:11:53.290 --> 00:11:58.290
to be readable by somebody else
besides my family, you know?

00:11:58.290 --> 00:12:02.550
So, a lot of that time was
spent doing a lot of research

00:12:02.550 --> 00:12:06.460
on additional parts of the book
that really kind of interested me.

00:12:06.460 --> 00:12:10.450
As soon as I knew that I
wanted the family to be fluent

00:12:10.450 --> 00:12:16.160
in sign language, I started to
research a lot about that aspect

00:12:16.160 --> 00:12:18.990
and way of communication,
the history of sign language.

00:12:18.990 --> 00:12:22.620
I should stop here to say that
I always talk about this book

00:12:22.620 --> 00:12:26.100
as if the idea came from
like a really outside source,

00:12:26.100 --> 00:12:29.530
and part of it did, but while I
was doing the research in this book

00:12:29.530 --> 00:12:31.260
and starting to write
about this book,

00:12:31.260 --> 00:12:34.100
I remember that there
is this family story.

00:12:34.100 --> 00:12:36.100
So my mother knows sign language.

00:12:36.100 --> 00:12:40.810
She's been fascinated with that
language from a really young age.

00:12:40.810 --> 00:12:43.480
And she, for a little while,
when they lived in this area,

00:12:43.480 --> 00:12:45.280
she actually went to
Gallaudet College

00:12:45.280 --> 00:12:47.820
for a little while in the 1970s.

00:12:47.820 --> 00:12:52.130
And when she and my father were
living in New York in the 1970s,

00:12:52.130 --> 00:12:55.090
she was taking sign language
classes at Hunter College

00:12:55.090 --> 00:12:58.690
and she actually got asked
to -- if she would --

00:12:58.690 --> 00:13:03.330
to apply for a job at a research
institute in West Chester

00:13:03.330 --> 00:13:05.800
where they did have
chimpanzees and they asked her

00:13:05.800 --> 00:13:08.300
if she would be interested in kind

00:13:08.300 --> 00:13:10.930
of working really closely
with that chimpanzee.

00:13:10.930 --> 00:13:13.490
And when they found out that
she had a daughter, a toddler,

00:13:13.490 --> 00:13:15.430
they got super excited and
wanted her to work with it.

00:13:15.430 --> 00:13:18.100
And the story in my family
was always that it was kind

00:13:18.100 --> 00:13:19.400
of like a throw away story.

00:13:19.400 --> 00:13:22.930
My mom is a really fascinating
person and has millions of stories

00:13:22.930 --> 00:13:25.030
like that where she'll just
kind of drop it in conversation.

00:13:25.030 --> 00:13:27.660
And we'll be like, "What
are you talking about?

00:13:27.660 --> 00:13:28.960
[Inaudible]."

00:13:28.960 --> 00:13:30.920
But the story with that is that
she thought about it and was kind

00:13:30.920 --> 00:13:34.270
of horrified with this idea of
bonding with another animal,

00:13:34.270 --> 00:13:37.610
and then having to give them
up at the end of the study.

00:13:37.610 --> 00:13:40.820
And especially of her child doing
that and having to give it up.

00:13:40.820 --> 00:13:43.890
So she said, "Absolutely not,
no, I would never do this."

00:13:43.890 --> 00:13:48.240
And the joke in our family was
always that my dad was really upset

00:13:48.240 --> 00:13:50.610
about it because we would
have gotten a free car

00:13:50.610 --> 00:13:51.930
and a free house in West Chester.

00:13:51.930 --> 00:13:53.730
And he's like, "We've could
have saved a lot of money

00:13:53.730 --> 00:13:55.770
for the year," so we
lived in New York.

00:13:55.770 --> 00:13:58.930
So, I knew a little bit
about sign language.

00:13:58.930 --> 00:14:01.080
My mom used sign language
around the house.

00:14:01.080 --> 00:14:02.660
When I went to work with
her, when she was --

00:14:02.660 --> 00:14:07.430 position:56%
she worked for many years at Perkins
School for the Blind in Boston,

00:14:07.430 --> 00:14:12.620
and while she was there, she worked
with a program with autistic adults

00:14:12.620 --> 00:14:16.460
and adults without much
access to language.

00:14:16.460 --> 00:14:18.730
So she actually used sign language
a lot there and I would to work

00:14:18.730 --> 00:14:21.180
with her and I would
see her use it a lot.

00:14:21.180 --> 00:14:24.120
And so I knew a little
bit about the language.

00:14:24.120 --> 00:14:27.240
I don't actually know how to use
it myself, but she still does.

00:14:27.240 --> 00:14:29.720
But as I was doing
more research about it,

00:14:29.720 --> 00:14:33.710
I found out that there was a
dialect of American sign language,

00:14:33.710 --> 00:14:35.230
African American sign language,

00:14:35.230 --> 00:14:38.610
that history of that language
was really fascinating.

00:14:38.610 --> 00:14:40.980
And that that the signs
are different

00:14:40.980 --> 00:14:45.020
and that the reason why
they're different is actually

00:14:45.020 --> 00:14:47.910
because you know, if you
know anything about history

00:14:47.910 --> 00:14:51.590 position:56%
of deaf Americans or deaf liberation
movements in this country,

00:14:51.590 --> 00:14:55.940
for a long time sign language was
not allowed in many deaf schools

00:14:55.940 --> 00:14:58.810
because people thought that
it was encouraging deaf people

00:14:58.810 --> 00:15:00.580
to stay amongst themselves.

00:15:00.580 --> 00:15:03.400
And so there's this whole
really interesting history

00:15:03.400 --> 00:15:07.260
around the identity around that.

00:15:07.260 --> 00:15:10.590
All that is to say that
many schools for the deaf

00:15:10.590 --> 00:15:12.620
for Black children
never had that ban.

00:15:12.620 --> 00:15:16.120
So a whole other kind of version
of the language spread up --

00:15:16.120 --> 00:15:19.340 position:56%
spread and grew and that whole
history was really interesting to me

00:15:19.340 --> 00:15:22.830
and something that I tried to bring
out and to talk about in the book.

00:15:22.830 --> 00:15:29.180
Because for me, the book is really
a lot about the limits of language,

00:15:29.180 --> 00:15:30.790
the limits of language
that we have even

00:15:30.790 --> 00:15:34.710 position:56%
when we have the best intentions for
the words that we're trying to use.

00:15:34.710 --> 00:15:41.260 position:56%
And how much people use language,
both to explain really uncomfortable

00:15:41.260 --> 00:15:45.980
and really hurtful situations,
and also to try and mask

00:15:45.980 --> 00:15:48.650
or minimize those situations.

00:15:48.650 --> 00:15:54.100
And I was at a class in Amherst on
Wednesday, I was talking to a class

00:15:54.100 --> 00:15:56.270
at Amherst and [inaudible],
one of the students said, "Oh,

00:15:56.270 --> 00:15:58.010
this book has a lot
of silences in it.

00:15:58.010 --> 00:16:00.520
There's a lot of moments where the
characters either don't say things

00:16:00.520 --> 00:16:05.390
to each other that they should say,
or they're just not able to finish

00:16:05.390 --> 00:16:07.120
or get back to a conversation."

00:16:07.120 --> 00:16:11.090
And that's kind of how I
experienced language a lot

00:16:11.090 --> 00:16:12.680
when I was writing this book

00:16:12.680 --> 00:16:15.000
and even before I started
writing this book.

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:18.700
You know, somebody who reads and
loves books and loves writing,

00:16:18.700 --> 00:16:21.250
there's still always felt like
there was some sort of limitation,

00:16:21.250 --> 00:16:24.340
that sometimes it seemed like the
books that I was so interested

00:16:24.340 --> 00:16:26.780
in engaging with, only went so far

00:16:26.780 --> 00:16:29.750
and that there were still
other questions to keep going

00:16:29.750 --> 00:16:31.540
and that I wanted answered.

00:16:31.540 --> 00:16:34.960
And for a long time, I think and
when I was probably a teenager,

00:16:34.960 --> 00:16:36.900
I was really mournful
about that and I got kind

00:16:36.900 --> 00:16:38.520
of like, "Well what can books do?

00:16:38.520 --> 00:16:41.630
Kind of where we got stuck here,
where can they kind of go?"

00:16:41.630 --> 00:16:44.970
And now as an adult and after
reading a little bit more

00:16:44.970 --> 00:16:47.130
and talking to writers
more, I realize that a lot

00:16:47.130 --> 00:16:49.070
of times writers themselves

00:16:49.070 --> 00:16:51.200
when they write books are
aware of those limitations.

00:16:51.200 --> 00:16:55.580
And that's actually kind of the
thing that keeps writing alive

00:16:55.580 --> 00:16:59.360
and keeps writing going is that
you read a book and you realize

00:16:59.360 --> 00:17:02.840
that it opens you up
hopefully to 10, or 11, or 12,

00:17:02.840 --> 00:17:04.810
or hundreds of more questions.

00:17:04.810 --> 00:17:07.720
And that your reading can
actually lead you kind

00:17:07.720 --> 00:17:09.230
of further and further.

00:17:09.230 --> 00:17:12.220
And that sense of kind
of never completion,

00:17:12.220 --> 00:17:16.340
kind of language always -- just
getting there but like not enough,

00:17:16.340 --> 00:17:19.270 position:56%
actually became a real strength for
me when I was thinking about writing

00:17:19.270 --> 00:17:21.020
and thinking about books.

00:17:21.020 --> 00:17:22.700
And so now I get really
excited when I --

00:17:22.700 --> 00:17:24.210
and when I read a book
and I close it

00:17:24.210 --> 00:17:26.960
and there's more questions
than I have answers.

00:17:26.960 --> 00:17:28.940
I always think of that James
Baldwin quote, which I'm going

00:17:28.940 --> 00:17:30.720
to totally butcher because
I did not write it down

00:17:30.720 --> 00:17:32.050
but I think it's something like,

00:17:32.050 --> 00:17:36.060
"Art is there to ask questions,
not answer them for us."

00:17:36.060 --> 00:17:40.030
So, that became really interesting
and really important to me

00:17:40.030 --> 00:17:42.960
for this project, for this
book as I was writing it was

00:17:42.960 --> 00:17:46.190
that hopefully this book is a
conversation with the reader.

00:17:46.190 --> 00:17:48.860
And hopefully this is
something where you read it

00:17:48.860 --> 00:17:50.430
and you can have additional
questions

00:17:50.430 --> 00:17:52.640
or ask people additional questions.

00:17:52.640 --> 00:17:57.310
There's -- I don't know if anyone
of you have seen Junot Diaz speak,

00:17:57.310 --> 00:18:02.010 position:56%
but he often tells a story when he
does his speeches where he's talking

00:18:02.010 --> 00:18:09.900 position:56%
about if he's teaching a complicated
text, when he used to teach

00:18:09.900 --> 00:18:12.440
at a commuter college and he
was teaching a complicated text

00:18:12.440 --> 00:18:13.880
and he would ask the class,

00:18:13.880 --> 00:18:16.840
"Does anybody understand
this -- what we just read?"

00:18:16.840 --> 00:18:19.050
Everybody would feel comfortable
raising their hand and saying,

00:18:19.050 --> 00:18:20.350
"No, I didn't understand."

00:18:20.350 --> 00:18:21.650
And they would have
a class discussion.

00:18:21.650 --> 00:18:22.950
That would be class.

00:18:22.950 --> 00:18:25.500
And then he said that when he
got to starting to teach at MIT,

00:18:25.500 --> 00:18:28.170
they would -- he would bring a
complicated text and he would say,

00:18:28.170 --> 00:18:29.500
"Does anybody understand
what we just read?"

00:18:29.500 --> 00:18:30.800
and everybody would say "Yes."

00:18:30.800 --> 00:18:32.420
And then he'd say, "Okay,
can anybody explain it?"

00:18:32.420 --> 00:18:33.750
And the room would go silent.

00:18:33.750 --> 00:18:36.470
And the conversation was
over because nobody wanted

00:18:36.470 --> 00:18:38.470
to admit what they didn't know

00:18:38.470 --> 00:18:40.920
or where the limits of
their knowledge were.

00:18:40.920 --> 00:18:44.890
And he talks also a lot
about kind of the importance

00:18:44.890 --> 00:18:46.510
of books having that ambiguity.

00:18:46.510 --> 00:18:49.730
How for him when he was a kid
and he was reading a book,

00:18:49.730 --> 00:18:53.600
when he came across a word that
he didn't know, he would assume

00:18:53.600 --> 00:18:57.360
that the writer had put that word
there so that you were supposed

00:18:57.360 --> 00:19:00.070
to close the book and go
ask somebody about it.

00:19:00.070 --> 00:19:02.750
And that was a chance for you to
have a conversation with somebody

00:19:02.750 --> 00:19:04.050
about a word that you didn't know

00:19:04.050 --> 00:19:05.350
and that's how you're
supposed to learn it.

00:19:05.350 --> 00:19:08.770
So, both of those kind of
ideas were really profound

00:19:08.770 --> 00:19:10.070
and really interesting to me.

00:19:10.070 --> 00:19:14.930
And really drive kind of the
way that this book came to be

00:19:14.930 --> 00:19:18.070
and how I hope this book
exists in the world.

00:19:18.070 --> 00:19:21.710
I got really worried about,
when I was writing this book,

00:19:21.710 --> 00:19:24.800
