00:23:35.500 --> 00:23:37.030
Charlotte.

00:23:37.030 --> 00:23:40.780
"This car doesn't feel
like ours," I said.

00:23:40.780 --> 00:23:45.240
"Well, it is now," my father said
with a sigh, "So get used to it."

00:23:45.240 --> 00:23:48.590
Outside of the car
it was dark and hot

00:23:48.590 --> 00:23:51.950
and early morning August
in Dorchester.

00:23:51.950 --> 00:23:56.280
Through the crack of the window, I
could smell every part of the city,

00:23:56.280 --> 00:24:00.860
every slab of asphalt, every
rotting plank of wood siding,

00:24:00.860 --> 00:24:05.610
every crumbling stucco wall,
every scarred and skinny tree.

00:24:05.610 --> 00:24:07.830
I could smell all of
it beginning to sweat.

00:24:07.830 --> 00:24:11.470
I sat back in my seat.

00:24:11.470 --> 00:24:13.190
I knew I was right.

00:24:13.190 --> 00:24:18.290
Our old car was a used silver
Chevy sedan, a dubious gift

00:24:18.290 --> 00:24:21.030
from my uncle Lyle, a mechanic.

00:24:21.030 --> 00:24:24.850
The Chevy's backseats were
balding, the foam cushions peeling

00:24:24.850 --> 00:24:28.650
with faded stickers from some
long discarded coloring book.

00:24:28.650 --> 00:24:32.620
The Chevy's body slumped over
its axis, slung way too low

00:24:32.620 --> 00:24:35.640
to the ground, so that when
you opened the car's doors,

00:24:35.640 --> 00:24:37.960
