but the cartilage wouldn't break.

00:25:29.430 --> 00:25:33.570
I shifted my legs, and the leather
skin of the seat stuck to the backs

00:25:33.570 --> 00:25:38.730
of my thighs, made a slow,
painful smack as I leaned forward.

00:25:38.730 --> 00:25:41.750
"They know we're no good
with animals, right?"

00:25:41.750 --> 00:25:44.750
I moved again and the
leather creaked beneath me.

00:25:44.750 --> 00:25:47.420
"I mean, you told them that?"

00:25:47.420 --> 00:25:48.720
"What are you talking about?"

00:25:48.720 --> 00:25:50.360
My mother rolled down her window,

00:25:50.360 --> 00:25:53.240
began to fuss with the
driver's side mirror.

00:25:53.240 --> 00:25:55.330
"We're great with animals."

00:25:55.330 --> 00:25:56.630
"We are not.

00:25:56.630 --> 00:25:58.900
We're terrible with pets."

00:25:58.900 --> 00:26:01.410
"Well, that's e because
we won't have a pet."

00:26:01.410 --> 00:26:03.590
My mother had been
saying this for weeks.

00:26:03.590 --> 00:26:05.440
"Charlie isn't a pet."

00:26:05.440 --> 00:26:07.910
"He's a research monkey,"
my father added.

00:26:07.910 --> 00:26:09.290
"He's a chimpanzee."

00:26:09.290 --> 00:26:11.090
This was my sister, Callie.

00:26:11.090 --> 00:26:13.260
"He's more than a pet,"
my mother corrected.

00:26:13.260 --> 00:26:16.110
"He's going to be like
a brother to you."

00:26:16.110 --> 00:26:19.490
My father said, "That's
going a bit far, Laurel."

00:26:19.490 --> 00:26:22.420
"What I'm trying to say," she
began, "is that we just have

00:26:22.420 --> 00:26:24.300
to treat him like one of us.

00:26:24.300 --> 00:26:26.400
Like he's part of our family.

00:26:26.400 --> 00:26:28.400
We just have to make
him feel like he's one

00:26:28.400 --> 00:26:30.980
of our own and he'll do e."

00:26:30.980 --> 00:26:33.440
"But all our pets die."

00:26:33.440 --> 00:26:34.740
"Charlotte."

00:26:34.740 --> 00:26:36.170
My mother was scanning
the street now.

00:26:36.170 --> 00:26:37.470
"It's true.

00:26:37.470 --> 00:26:40.690
That rabbit you bought me when I
was e and Callie was born."

00:26:40.690 --> 00:26:41.990
"He was depressed."

00:26:41.990 --> 00:26:43.340
My father turned in his seat.

00:26:43.340 --> 00:26:46.750
"It was because we kept him
under the kitchen counter."

00:26:46.750 --> 00:26:50.640 position:56%
My father had a notebook open in his
lap, the pages turned to the start

00:26:50.640 --> 00:26:54.930
of a geometry lesson plan, but
he hadn't written anything yet.

00:26:54.930 --> 00:26:57.350
Over his shoulder, I could
see where he'd drawn a grove

00:26:57.350 --> 00:27:01.280
of interlocking pineapples
in the sheet's margins.

00:27:01.280 --> 00:27:04.700
"In our defense," my mother
said, "we had to keep him there.

00:27:04.700 --> 00:27:06.790
We just didn't have the space."

00:27:06.790 --> 00:27:09.320 position:56%
She tugged at her side mirror again.

00:27:09.320 --> 00:27:14.240 position:56%
She frowned, made an appreciative
"ah," and rolled her window back up.

00:27:14.240 --> 00:27:16.550
She touched a button
on the dashboard,

00:27:16.550 --> 00:27:19.160
and the mirror gave a delicate
little shudder and began

00:27:19.160 --> 00:27:21.770
to angle itself toward her.

00:27:21.770 --> 00:27:24.600
She glanced over at
my father, grinned.

00:27:24.600 --> 00:27:26.710
"Very nice," he said.

00:27:26.710 --> 00:27:29.410
I stuck my head in the
space between them.

00:27:29.410 --> 00:27:32.400
"That rabbit died because
he ate his own fur.

00:27:32.400 --> 00:27:33.700
He choked on it.

00:27:33.700 --> 00:27:36.470
He died because he
choked on himself."

00:27:36.470 --> 00:27:37.770
"Is that true?"

00:27:37.770 --> 00:27:39.150
Callie strained against
her seat belt,

00:27:39.150 --> 00:27:41.160 position:56%
trying to catch what we were saying.

00:27:41.160 --> 00:27:42.680
"No." My mother swatted at me.

00:27:42.680 --> 00:27:45.230
"Charlotte, get back there,
get back in your seat.

00:27:45.230 --> 00:27:46.530
Put your seat belt on.

00:27:46.530 --> 00:27:48.290
You're upsetting your sister."

00:27:48.290 --> 00:27:51.690
We didn't even have seat
belts in the old car.

00:27:51.690 --> 00:27:56.220
I ran mine across my chest,
clicked the buckle closed.

00:27:56.220 --> 00:28:00.520
I waited. Then I said,
"Dad's h."

00:28:00.520 --> 00:28:05.170
My mother shot me a warning
glance in the rearview mirror.

00:28:05.170 --> 00:28:08.300
"Dad was in charge of the
h and it still died."

00:28:08.300 --> 00:28:09.980
No one answered me.

00:28:09.980 --> 00:28:14.060
After a while I said,
"And it didn't even die.

00:28:14.060 --> 00:28:16.670
It just kind of ked away."

00:28:16.670 --> 00:28:19.470
"I think I'm going to
be sick," Callie moaned.

00:28:19.470 --> 00:28:20.770
"He had mange."

00:28:20.770 --> 00:28:24.390
My father turned again in his
seat, trying to catch Callie's eye.

00:28:24.390 --> 00:28:25.690
"I've told you this before.

00:28:25.690 --> 00:28:29.000
He already had it when we brought
him home from the pet store."

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:30.360
But I persisted.

00:28:30.360 --> 00:28:34.590
"Mom had to take that h out of
the tank and put him in a paper bag

00:28:34.590 --> 00:28:37.250
and bury him at the park
because he was so messed

00:28:37.250 --> 00:28:39.650
up he would have polluted
our toilets.

00:28:39.650 --> 00:28:43.360
We made a h too
sick for a toilet, Mom."

00:28:43.360 --> 00:28:45.770
"I'm going to be sick,"
Callie declared.

00:28:45.770 --> 00:28:47.190
"Charlotte, no talking."

00:28:47.190 --> 00:28:49.660
My mother leaned forward
and switched on the radio

00:28:49.660 --> 00:28:54.420
and a too deep voice
intoned, "W-I-L-D Boston."

00:28:54.420 --> 00:28:56.900
That station was at the
top of the list of things

00:28:56.900 --> 00:28:58.680
that my mother forbade us.

00:28:58.680 --> 00:29:02.080
"Nothing but booty music," she'd
say, a di-missal that made me

00:29:02.080 --> 00:29:05.000
and Callie squirm in embarrassment.

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:07.930
Now, though, she turned the
volume up until the sound buzzed

00:29:07.930 --> 00:29:11.390
over us, drowning out our words.

00:29:11.390 --> 00:29:13.370
My last piece of evidence I signed

00:29:13.370 --> 00:29:16.710
to Callie underneath the
stutter of a drum machine.

00:29:16.710 --> 00:29:19.130 position:56%
The mice, I explained with my hands.

00:29:19.130 --> 00:29:23.830 position:56%
We had mice and they died of heart
attacks because they mated too much.

00:29:23.830 --> 00:29:27.180
They fucked, and here I spelled it
out because I didn't know the sign

00:29:27.180 --> 00:29:30.820
for that yet, they
f-u-c-k-e-d to death.

00:29:30.820 --> 00:29:32.570
How did they do that?

00:29:32.570 --> 00:29:34.130
Callie signed back.

00:29:34.130 --> 00:29:37.240
I shook my head and turned
my face to the window.

00:29:37.240 --> 00:29:40.510
Okay, so that's Callie's section.

00:29:40.510 --> 00:29:44.510
[ Applause ]

00:29:44.510 --> 00:29:53.010
And then I'll read from
Nymphadora's section.

00:29:53.010 --> 00:30:01.270
So she is a -- she's living
in the Berkshires in 1929.

00:30:01.270 --> 00:30:03.640
And I think that's
all you need to know.

00:30:03.640 --> 00:30:08.160
I think it will become
pretty clear as we go on.

00:30:09.630 --> 00:30:12.530
My mother was a Star of a Morning.

00:30:12.530 --> 00:30:15.310
My father was a sadder night.

00:30:15.310 --> 00:30:20.480
I was first an infant of delivery
star, and then I was a girl star,

00:30:20.480 --> 00:30:24.830
then a young lady star, and three
years ago, right before mama

00:30:24.830 --> 00:30:30.000
and pop drank a jigger of cyanide
each, I became in my own right,

00:30:30.000 --> 00:30:33.300
a full-blown star of the
morning, Fifth House,

00:30:33.300 --> 00:30:36.100
Second Quadrant Division,
northeastern launch

00:30:36.100 --> 00:30:39.020
of the colored hamlet of
Spring City in the town

00:30:39.020 --> 00:30:41.950
of Cortland County, Massachusetts.

00:30:41.950 --> 00:30:46.570
After my parents committed suicide,
I declared, if only to myself,

00:30:46.570 --> 00:30:49.470
that I was no longer
a Star of the Morning.

00:30:49.470 --> 00:30:53.300
But even now, three years on,
I can't stop wearing my pin.

00:30:53.300 --> 00:30:55.410
During the day, while
I'm teaching class,

00:30:55.410 --> 00:30:58.410
it's hidden under my shirt
collar, pinned right up close

00:30:58.410 --> 00:31:00.320
to the front of my throat.

00:31:00.320 --> 00:31:03.620
At night, after I've dressed
my hair and put it in its cap

00:31:03.620 --> 00:31:05.970
after I've rubbed my face
first with cold cream

00:31:05.970 --> 00:31:10.790
and then a worn oily piece of
chamois, I do what mama showed me.

00:31:10.790 --> 00:31:14.570
I stand in front of the mirror,
my skin all greasy and soft,

00:31:14.570 --> 00:31:17.650
and take off the pin while
staring at my reflection.

00:31:17.650 --> 00:31:22.250 position:56%
A star of the morning is never
allowed to look directly at her pin.

00:31:22.250 --> 00:31:27.190 position:56%
My pin is a small, brass knot, filed
down to look like a burst of light,

00:31:27.190 --> 00:31:29.630
with a rusty garnet in the middle.

00:31:29.630 --> 00:31:33.290
When I was an infant star, I would
stand in the mirror beside mama,

00:31:33.290 --> 00:31:37.200
watching our reflections' fingers
at work unfastening our pins,

00:31:37.200 --> 00:31:38.600
and I was filled with love.

00:31:38.600 --> 00:31:42.470
I thought it was the most
beautiful thing in the world.

00:31:42.470 --> 00:31:45.390
Mama told me it was
better than a diamond.

00:31:45.390 --> 00:31:49.340
Stars of the Morning always take
off their pins before they sleep,

00:31:49.340 --> 00:31:51.700
and always before their
evening prayers so as not

00:31:51.700 --> 00:31:54.020
to make a false idol out of it.

00:31:54.020 --> 00:31:57.940
Now, when I take off my pin, I
place it on my nightstand and then,

00:31:57.940 --> 00:32:01.300
if I was to follow what mama
taught me, I am supposed to reflect

00:32:01.300 --> 00:32:04.980
on my moral failings during the
day, and recite the Lord's Prayer,

00:32:04.980 --> 00:32:09.900
because Stars of the Morning are
good Christian [inaudible] women.

00:32:09.900 --> 00:32:12.930
But no one, if they could read my
thoughts would call me a Christian

00:32:12.930 --> 00:32:15.950
anymore, and besides, I
don't believe in prayer.

00:32:15.950 --> 00:32:21.140
So during this bit of the routine,
I try to just sit quiet on my bed.

00:32:21.140 --> 00:32:24.380
But after years of ritual,
I can't help myself.

00:32:24.380 --> 00:32:27.920
Even when I'm dumb, the blood
in my ears pounds out the rhythm

00:32:27.920 --> 00:32:30.400
of "Our Father, who art in heaven."

00:32:30.400 --> 00:32:34.010
To drown out these pious
cadences, in my head,

00:32:34.010 --> 00:32:37.700
I sometimes chant the obscene
version I learned as girl.

00:32:37.700 --> 00:32:40.950
"Our Father, who farts in heaven,
Horesch [phonetic] be his name."

00:32:40.950 --> 00:32:46.520
I am a 36-year-old, unmarried,
orphaned, negro school teacher,

00:32:46.520 --> 00:32:50.250
in charge of a roomful of
impressionable young colored minds,

00:32:50.250 --> 00:32:52.180
and every night, I sing a dirty,

00:32:52.180 --> 00:32:54.580
nursery rhyme to help
me go to sleep.

00:32:54.580 --> 00:32:58.390
It is enough to laugh if I did
not always feel like weeping.

00:32:58.390 --> 00:33:01.480
The time for prayer
over, ready for bed,

00:33:01.480 --> 00:33:04.820
the last thing I do before I
lay down and blow out the light,

00:33:04.820 --> 00:33:07.770
is to stand before the mirror
again, and pinch the pin

00:33:07.770 --> 00:33:10.340
between my fingers, and
very carefully stick it

00:33:10.340 --> 00:33:11.860
to the lace collar of nightgown.

00:33:11.860 --> 00:33:15.790
I've slept with the pin for
as long as I can remember.

00:33:15.790 --> 00:33:19.550
At the base of my neck, just
below the collarbone, is a livid,

00:33:19.550 --> 00:33:24.150
red line from its sharpest
end, drawing on me.

00:33:24.150 --> 00:33:27.070
My best memory is of initiation.

00:33:27.070 --> 00:33:28.950
I was 7 years old.

00:33:28.950 --> 00:33:31.340
We stood in front of the
church basement door,

00:33:31.340 --> 00:33:35.650
on a lawn so bright you could
see the green even in dusk.

00:33:35.650 --> 00:33:40.130 position:56%
My mother was the most powerful star
in Spring City, so I was the head

00:33:40.130 --> 00:33:43.280
of the line, even though
I didn't want to be.

00:33:43.280 --> 00:33:45.590
I was terrified.

00:33:45.590 --> 00:33:48.490
An older girl had once told me
that to become an infant star,

00:33:48.490 --> 00:33:51.100
they set your hair on fire.

00:33:51.100 --> 00:33:55.140 position:56%
Her friends said the big women stars
made you shake a dead lady's hand,

00:33:55.140 --> 00:33:58.470
the hand of the very
first star who ever lived.

00:33:58.470 --> 00:34:01.170
"The big women stars keep it
in a special box," she said,

00:34:01.170 --> 00:34:03.870
"and when you shake
it, the bones crunch

00:34:03.870 --> 00:34:05.880
and the dust gets on your fingers.

00:34:05.880 --> 00:34:08.200
The dead lady's dust is
what makes you a star."

00:34:08.200 --> 00:34:11.300
I had asked mama about
all of these rumors

00:34:11.300 --> 00:34:15.400
and she told me they were nonsense,
and those girls were just jealous.

00:34:15.400 --> 00:34:16.930
Their mothers were loose women

00:34:16.930 --> 00:34:19.490
and the girls had proven
themselves unruly.

00:34:19.490 --> 00:34:22.620
And so they could never
become an infant star like me.

00:34:22.620 --> 00:34:25.300
But I remained uneasy
and when I pressed mama,

00:34:25.300 --> 00:34:29.480
she still wouldn't tell me exactly
what happened at initiation.

00:34:29.480 --> 00:34:32.990
All my life, I thought we
had no secrets between us.

00:34:32.990 --> 00:34:37.250 position:56%
The year before when our tabby Dina,
birthed a litter, she told me frank

00:34:37.250 --> 00:34:40.300
and shrew how cats
and people were made.

00:34:40.300 --> 00:34:44.340 position:56%
She told me how the universe came to
be, and where our earth stood in it.

00:34:44.340 --> 00:34:47.650
And that God did not live in the
sun, but in the breath and air

00:34:47.650 --> 00:34:50.320
and dust around and within us.

00:34:50.320 --> 00:34:54.240
"The sun is just a very bright
ball," she told me, which was more

00:34:54.240 --> 00:34:56.950
than the other mothers
told their children.

00:34:56.950 --> 00:34:59.190
But she wouldn't tell me
about becoming a star,

00:34:59.190 --> 00:35:01.020
as many times as I asked her.

00:35:01.020 --> 00:35:04.520
For initiation, I wore
a white lace dress

00:35:04.520 --> 00:35:08.410
and patent leather shoes mama
ordered special from Boston.

00:35:08.410 --> 00:35:12.070
Nine little girls pressed against
my back all breathing heavy.

00:35:12.070 --> 00:35:16.330
We had to fast for a day and
a night before initiation.

00:35:16.330 --> 00:35:18.740
According to the bylaws of
the Stars of the Morning,

00:35:18.740 --> 00:35:22.450
infant stars are supposed to
consume only milk and honey,

00:35:22.450 --> 00:35:25.060
and they have to chant,
"I'm a vessel for the light

00:35:25.060 --> 00:35:27.480
of our Lord," before they drink it.

00:35:27.480 --> 00:35:30.440
But no one in Spring City could
afford honey, so we drank our milk

00:35:30.440 --> 00:35:32.920
with raw brown sugar instead.

00:35:32.920 --> 00:35:35.950
I breathed the rotten sweetness
of it on the other children's spit

00:35:35.950 --> 00:35:37.250
and in their girlish sweat.

00:35:37.250 --> 00:35:42.620
I squeezed my eyes shut very
tight and kept them that way

00:35:42.620 --> 00:35:45.900
until I heard the basement
door of the church rumble open.

00:35:45.900 --> 00:35:49.710
I heard the girls behind me
breath quicker, talk faster.

00:35:49.710 --> 00:35:52.810
I felt something brushing
against my hand.

00:35:52.810 --> 00:35:56.140
"The dead woman," I thought, but
the hand that took mine was fat

00:35:56.140 --> 00:35:58.960
and warm, and it led me very
carefully down the steps

00:35:58.960 --> 00:36:01.640
and into the church basement.

00:36:01.640 --> 00:36:05.470
Once I was there, it smelled the
same as it always had, like earth

00:36:05.470 --> 00:36:09.190
and the moths that ate the choir
robes, and the greening tint

00:36:09.190 --> 00:36:11.000
of the church collection plate.

00:36:11.000 --> 00:36:14.730
I almost opened my
eyes, but a voice said,

00:36:14.730 --> 00:36:17.510
"Keep your lights closed,
infant star."

00:36:17.510 --> 00:36:21.090
Right beneath my chin, I felt
a point of warmth and I knew

00:36:21.090 --> 00:36:24.860
that it was someone holding
a candle close to my face.

00:36:24.860 --> 00:36:28.400
This comforted me somehow
to know the light was near.

00:36:28.400 --> 00:36:32.980 position:56%
I heard the other girls stumble down
the stairs, one by one, most gasped,

00:36:32.980 --> 00:36:36.070
a few of the very young
ones started to cry.

00:36:36.070 --> 00:36:38.960
Then I heard the basement
door rumble shut.

00:36:38.960 --> 00:36:42.770
I opened my eyes and I laughed.

00:36:42.770 --> 00:36:45.620
I laughed because even though
the room smelled just the same,

00:36:45.620 --> 00:36:48.990
when I opened my eyes, I saw it had
become the most beautiful place I

00:36:48.990 --> 00:36:51.690
have ever been in my
life before or since.

00:36:51.690 --> 00:36:53.610
It wasn't dark.

00:36:53.610 --> 00:36:56.280
The earth walls were
covered in white paper.

00:36:56.280 --> 00:36:59.220
What seemed like a thousand
candles were lit all around us,

00:36:59.220 --> 00:37:02.310
in tiny glass and tin lanterns.

00:37:02.310 --> 00:37:06.320 position:56%
Strings of white hydrangea were
threaded across the top of the room.

00:37:06.320 --> 00:37:09.710
Clouds hung down from the ceiling
and for a moment I thought,

00:37:09.710 --> 00:37:12.440
"Mama's brought down the
very sky to greet me."

00:37:12.440 --> 00:37:16.270
But then I saw that it was just
tool from Ms. Vera's dress shop,

00:37:16.270 --> 00:37:19.610
double up on itself
to seem like heaven.

00:37:19.610 --> 00:37:22.970
We jumbled ourselves all up
until we formed a new line.

00:37:22.970 --> 00:37:24.800
I was now in the middle.

00:37:24.800 --> 00:37:29.520
Mama strode up before us in a long,
white robe, trimmed with yellow.

00:37:29.520 --> 00:37:31.890
She held a gold bound
Bible in her hands.

00:37:31.890 --> 00:37:35.840
She opened a page at random and one
by one, we had to hover a finger

00:37:35.840 --> 00:37:38.110
over the Bible, let it fall down,

00:37:38.110 --> 00:37:40.830
and then read from
whichever passage we chose.

00:37:40.830 --> 00:37:43.380 position:56%
The passage gave us our secret name;

00:37:43.380 --> 00:37:46.340
the name only other
stars knew us by.

00:37:46.340 --> 00:37:50.230
The poor girl before me chose
Herod, and she cried and cried

00:37:50.230 --> 00:37:54.180
because she was going to have to go
by the name of a known baby killer.

00:37:54.180 --> 00:37:58.540 position:56%
I thought for certain mama would let
her pick again, but she only looked

00:37:58.540 --> 00:38:01.740
on sternly as another star
patted the little girl's back,

00:38:01.740 --> 00:38:03.900
and told her some quickly
made up nonsense

00:38:03.900 --> 00:38:05.830
about this being a
splendid opportunity

00:38:05.830 --> 00:38:08.140
to restore honor to the name.

00:38:08.140 --> 00:38:12.150
I was relieved then when
I picked Nymphadora.

00:38:12.150 --> 00:38:15.420
My real name is Ellen, but
Nymphadora is so much better.

00:38:15.420 --> 00:38:18.410
I bet you didn't know there
was a Nymphadora in the Bible.

00:38:18.410 --> 00:38:21.850
There is, Colossians 4:15.

00:38:21.850 --> 00:38:24.640
Later, I found out our
Bible was a mistranslation.

00:38:24.640 --> 00:38:28.370
It should have read Nympha, and
Nympha should have been a man.

00:38:28.370 --> 00:38:32.470
It was by some lucky magic that I
got so fine a name as Nymphadora

00:38:32.470 --> 00:38:35.170
of the Spring City Stars.

00:38:35.170 --> 00:38:38.800
Nymphadora sounded beautiful
and elegant and pretty and peek.

00:38:38.800 --> 00:38:43.070
I liked that the Nymphadora in our
Bible ran a church in her own home.

00:38:43.070 --> 00:38:45.610
I was proud of the name but
when I turned a threw a smile

00:38:45.610 --> 00:38:47.470
at mama, she did not return it.

00:38:47.470 --> 00:38:50.810
When we were all newly
named, mama inspected the ten

00:38:50.810 --> 00:38:53.150
of us and still did not speak.

00:38:53.150 --> 00:38:56.360
She raised her hand and Ms.
Vera and another Star rolled

00:38:56.360 --> 00:39:00.480
out a tea table stacked with
food, real food, bowls of potatoes

00:39:00.480 --> 00:39:04.110
and biscuits and a lanky turkey
with its bony ankles wrapped

00:39:04.110 --> 00:39:06.400
in paper to keep its marrow warm.

00:39:06.400 --> 00:39:11.280
Our deflated stomachs milk lined
in sugary, leapt in revolt,

00:39:11.280 --> 00:39:12.970
but mama wouldn't let us eat.

00:39:12.970 --> 00:39:16.030
Instead, she stood in
front of the table.

00:39:16.030 --> 00:39:18.970
"Girls," she said, "you
are almost infant stars.

00:39:18.970 --> 00:39:21.450
Do you know what makes
a star shine?"

00:39:21.450 --> 00:39:22.750
No one answered.

00:39:22.750 --> 00:39:26.440
We were all watching the spread
behind her, too hungry to speak.

00:39:26.440 --> 00:39:28.880
"Girls," she said, "I've
asked you a question.

00:39:28.880 --> 00:39:33.330
A tenet of being an infant star is
to speak when you are spoken to.

00:39:33.330 --> 00:39:34.630
So we will begin again.

00:39:34.630 --> 00:39:36.380
What makes a star shine?"

00:39:36.380 --> 00:39:40.000
The newly named Herod
sniffed loudly, wiped the snot

00:39:40.000 --> 00:39:41.940
from her face, "The
light of heaven?"

00:39:41.940 --> 00:39:43.550
she offered cautiously?

00:39:43.550 --> 00:39:47.440
It was a good guess, as we'd had
to drone this phrase incessantly

00:39:47.440 --> 00:39:50.320
for the past few days as we fasted.

00:39:50.320 --> 00:39:51.620
"No," mama said.

00:39:51.620 --> 00:39:53.860
"No, not the light of heaven.

00:39:53.860 --> 00:39:56.090
What makes a Star of
the Morning shine,

00:39:56.090 --> 00:39:59.880
what makes an infant star shine
among all the other pieces of dust

00:39:59.880 --> 00:40:03.070
and dirt and rock that
are our Lord's creations,

00:40:03.070 --> 00:40:06.370
is self-control, denial.

00:40:06.370 --> 00:40:09.350
Denial built up inside
little infant stars like you,

00:40:09.350 --> 00:40:12.880
makes your moral fiber
strong like flint,

00:40:12.880 --> 00:40:17.050
so that when the world tests you,
when the world rubs up against you,

00:40:17.050 --> 00:40:20.370
all vicious and sharp,
and everything within you,

00:40:20.370 --> 00:40:24.880
everything is telling you to give
in, all your desire is to give in,

00:40:24.880 --> 00:40:26.600
do you know what happens?

00:40:26.600 --> 00:40:28.030
You don't give in.

00:40:28.030 --> 00:40:29.840
You don't become soft.

00:40:29.840 --> 00:40:31.900
You ignore your desires.

00:40:31.900 --> 00:40:36.850
The world's trials stir up light
in you so strong, so pure, so true,

00:40:36.850 --> 00:40:38.950
no man on earth could put it out.

00:40:38.950 --> 00:40:43.740
Denial of your desires is what
makes an infant star shine."

00:40:43.740 --> 00:40:47.670 position:56%
Mama leaned up against the table
and crossed her arms over her chest.

00:40:47.670 --> 00:40:51.530
She lifted her chin up to the
paper clouds and began to declaim.

00:40:51.530 --> 00:40:55.060
And even though she was my mother
and even though I worshipped her,

00:40:55.060 --> 00:40:58.660
I wanted to groan because I was a
smart little star, and I could read

00:40:58.660 --> 00:41:02.310
between the lines and see
despite the turkey's paper socks,

00:41:02.310 --> 00:41:04.600
promising meat kept
warm, we weren't going

00:41:04.600 --> 00:41:07.050 position:56%
to be eating anything, anytime soon.

00:41:07.050 --> 00:41:10.620
And when we finally did, it
would most certainly be cold.

00:41:10.620 --> 00:41:13.290
The very first star
denied herself everything

00:41:13.290 --> 00:41:16.370
so that she could be a
beacon of light for others.

00:41:16.370 --> 00:41:19.280
Her name was Mary Whitman
and she was a slave.

00:41:19.280 --> 00:41:21.230
Herod gasped at this.

00:41:21.230 --> 00:41:24.350
We were negroes it was true, but
we were all northern negroes,

00:41:24.350 --> 00:41:27.510
born of at least two
generations of freed men.

00:41:27.510 --> 00:41:31.280
Those with slavery closer to
them than that, kept it hidden.

00:41:31.280 --> 00:41:35.310
The first Emancipation Day
was nearly 40 years past.

00:41:35.310 --> 00:41:37.360
Slaves were the Israelites
in the Bible.

00:41:37.360 --> 00:41:40.400
They were the figures drawn in
quick blurry clouds of black ink

00:41:40.400 --> 00:41:41.800
in the illustrated editions

00:41:41.800 --> 00:41:44.750
of "Uncle Tom's Cabin"
we read in school.

00:41:44.750 --> 00:41:48.240
Though we understood that some of
us were once them, and that we had

00:41:48.240 --> 00:41:51.470
to bake cakes every
church bazaar for those

00:41:51.470 --> 00:41:56.190
who were still pretty much them,
it never occurred to us as children

00:41:56.190 --> 00:41:58.010
that slaves could live
in Spring City,

00:41:58.010 --> 00:42:01.680
Massachusetts any more
than camels could.

00:42:01.680 --> 00:42:04.400
"Yes," mama said, "she was
a slave and she ran away

00:42:04.400 --> 00:42:06.260
and came here to the north.

00:42:06.260 --> 00:42:09.470
But in order to run, she had
to deny herself everything.

00:42:09.470 --> 00:42:11.830
She had to deny herself love.

00:42:11.830 --> 00:42:14.540
She had a mother and father
and husband and little babies

00:42:14.540 --> 00:42:17.260
and she had to leave them behind.

00:42:17.260 --> 00:42:20.190
She had to deny herself love
and she ran and she ran,

00:42:20.190 --> 00:42:23.930
and when she came here, when she
came to the north, she was so full

00:42:23.930 --> 00:42:27.200
of light from her trials
that she became a star.

00:42:27.200 --> 00:42:30.520 position:56%
And she began this sisterhood to
teach other negro women how to shine

00:42:30.520 --> 00:42:34.450
like her, because in order for the
negro race to survive and thrive,

00:42:34.450 --> 00:42:37.240
we need a hundred stars,
a thousand stars,

00:42:37.240 --> 00:42:39.890
full of light to show
others the way."

00:42:39.890 --> 00:42:42.850
Mama rested against the table
and I heard the wood groan,

00:42:42.850 --> 00:42:45.250
and just a whiff, just
the tiniest hint

00:42:45.250 --> 00:42:47.730
of melted butter filled the air.

00:42:47.730 --> 00:42:49.820
"Not everyone can be a
star," she continued.

00:42:49.820 --> 00:42:53.120
"Not everyone can be so
strong as to deny themselves

00:42:53.120 --> 00:42:55.760
to make sure the negro
race survives.

00:42:55.760 --> 00:42:58.210
But we believe you infant
stars have the potential

00:42:58.210 --> 00:43:00.710
to become Stars of the Morning."

00:43:00.710 --> 00:43:02.780
And here, mama gestured to Ms. Dora

00:43:02.780 --> 00:43:06.300
who brought her a wooden backed
chair, which mama sat down on,

00:43:06.300 --> 00:43:09.310
arranged her skirts,
made herself comfortable.

00:43:09.310 --> 00:43:12.250
And I cannot remember the rest
of the speech from the night,

00:43:12.250 --> 00:43:13.550
because my attention was taken

00:43:13.550 --> 00:43:16.920
up with keeping my lips pressed
together and sucking hard

00:43:16.920 --> 00:43:19.410
on my own tongue to
keep from standing up,

00:43:19.410 --> 00:43:22.330
pushing my own mother aside,
and lapping up the mounds

00:43:22.330 --> 00:43:24.190
of potatoes stacked behind her.

00:43:24.190 --> 00:43:26.510
Okay, that's the end
of that section.

